    <item>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://mastodon.jakewharton.com/@jw/115868556591980325</guid>
      <link>https://mastodon.jakewharton.com/@jw/115868556591980325</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 10 Jan 2026 02:57:44 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;It's interesting seeing Zig folk laud their &lt;code&gt;assert&lt;/code&gt; function in contrast to C's &lt;code&gt;assert&lt;/code&gt; macro, when it seems like in Kotlin the &lt;code&gt;assert&lt;/code&gt; function behavior is criticized in comparison to Java's &lt;code&gt;assert&lt;/code&gt; language keyword. I definitely want the macro/Java-like behavior but with a lambda syntax to make the effects (or lack thereof) more obvious.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://cryptocode.github.io/blog/docs/assert/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" translate="no"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;cryptocode.github.io/blog/docs&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;/assert/&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://publicobject.com/2019/11/18/kotlins-assert-is-not-like-javas-assert/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" translate="no"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;publicobject.com/2019/11/18/ko&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;tlins-assert-is-not-like-javas-assert/&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;</description>
    </item>
